The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | Briefs
                                                                                                                       7                                                                                                        
	Karachi: Banned former captain Shoaib Malik was seen as a negative character and a bad influence on the Pakistan team by senior players like Shahid Afridi and Mohammed Yousuf, a leaked video of a PCB inquiry committees proceedings has revealed. The video has statements by former coaches Intikhab Alam and Aaqib Javed and players Rana Naved, Yousuf, Afridi and Malik himself. From their comments it becomes apparent that Malik was the most unpopular person in the team. Malik, who is serving a one-year ban for indiscipline, was described as someone who promoted politics.        
	Karachi: Pakistani pacer Shoaib Akhtar has approached a spiritual healer for the treatment of his chronic knee pain which could not be cured even after a major surgery in England last year.        
	Calcutta: The Indian cricket Board Tuesday appointed retired IPS officer Ranjit Kumar Das as its full-time security advisor. His previous assignment was as security advisor to the Organising Committee of the Commonwealth Games.        
	Kochi: Dav Whatmore, the Kolkata Knight Riders coach, Tuesday said players should learn to strike a balance between cricket and partying. The players should put in their 100 per cent for matches, he said.         
	Duesseldorf: John Isner and Sam Querrey beat Carsten Ball and Paul Hanley 5-7, 6-4, 10-8 in a tiebreaker on Monday to give the US a 2-1 Red Group victory over Australia in the World Team Cup.     
	Each series in the round-robin format consists of two singles and a doubles match, played over two days. The winner of each group  the second one is Blue  will meet in Saturdays final.        
	Buenos Aires: David Nalbandian has pulled out of the French Open with a left hamstring injury, the Argentine announced on his website on Monday. He said he hopes to return in time to play Wimbledon, which begins June 21.        
	New Delhi: Indian GM R.R. Laxman took the gold medal while Russias Pavel Maletin won the overall title in the Parsvnath Commonwealth Chess Championship that concluded Tuesday. Although Maletin and Laxman were tied on nine points each, the Indian got the medal since Russia is not a part of the Commonwealth.        
	New Delhi: Indias Saurav Ghosal shocked Malaysias Md Azlan Iskandar 11-9, 4-11, 11-8, 11-2 to book a place in the pre-quarter finals of the Sky Open in Cairo. Before Tuesdays win, Ghosal had suffered four successive Tour defeats against the Malaysian.  
